Changing my estimate again, the previous calculations had an error.Simply put if the GDP growth contracts by more than 0.7% vs previous quarter the annual GDP growth for Q4 will be less than 2%. If it contracts by more than 2.6% then the annual GDP will turn negativeGoldman`s forecast is 1.7% which they say is below consensushttps://in.investing.com/news/china-new-covid-guidelines-seen-as-a-significant-step-towards-full-reopening-432SI-3466799RHI group forecasts a 2% dip vs last quarter conservatively which again means that the annual growth will be 0.7% for Q4https://rhg.com/research/now-for-the-hard-part/Nomura forecasts a 2.4% growth for Q4, but this note is a month old and they call their forecast below consensus. The 4.8% from Q1 will be in the numbers. There are supply interruptions due to the weather, water and energy issues this quarter, so it will be slow in Q2. Also this has ruined crops so there may be a food issue later in the year. And if it doesn’t rain enough in the right places the water and energy problems will propagate. With the world elsewhere also have ing problems demand could start to get hit as well as supply. To be honest it doesn’t look that promising for China this year.
According to World Bank, the GDP growth is expected to rebound from the 0.4 of q2.
Was 0.4% growth in Q2 and anomaly or part of a trend? My guess is it’s probably part of a trend given the pressures on the economy, but I’m factoring in some uncertainty about this.
